  Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":23,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice Lancaster was born in 1432, in Westmorland, England, her father, Hugh Lancaster, was 32 and her mother, Lady Elizabeth Betham, was 34. She married James Clyfton in 1450, in Lancashire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1462, in England, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1432–1462":"1432–1462","1428–1491":"1428–1491","1402–1490":"1402–1490","1456–1526":"1456–1526","1457–1490":"1457–1490","1458–1490":"1458–1490","1400–1483":"1400–1483","1398–1464":"1398–1464","1462":"1462","1450":"1450","1483":"1483","1491":"1491","1 March 1457":"1. märts 1457","1490":"1490","1458":"1458","1457":"1457","1402":"1402","1456":"1456","1455":"1455","1400":"1400","1432":"1432","1464":"1464","1398":"1